       Change Summary Explanation
       FY 2024: -$28.662M Congressional Directed Reduction for: -$18.8M incentive fees excess to need; -$9.8M overestimation of A&AS.
       FY 2025: -$52.079M for Full-Year CR Agreement: -$20.0M ECO carryover; -$6.179M Schedule incentive ahead of need; -$25.9M Mission payload termination.
       FY 2026: -$4.269M; Advisory and Assistance Services (A&AS) reductions to promote efficiencies and advance the policies of the Administration in alignment EO
       14222, "Implementing the President's Department of Government Efficiency Cost Efficiency Initiative.
       FY 2026: -$2.092M Federally Funded Research and Development Center (FFRDC) reduction
       FY 2026: -$9.921M to realign funding to PEs 1206399SF and 1206771SF for increased transparency and efficient execution of basic operating costs for Space
       Systems Integration Office enterprise engineering support and for Commercial Space Office industry outreach and innovation support respectively.
       FY2026: -$1.456M for inflation rate adjustments.
       FY 2026: -$0.121M for USSF higher priorities.

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2024     FY 2025      FY 2026
Title: Next-Gen OPIR GEO                                                                                                               691.069     458.727      432.073
Description: Development of the Next-Generation Overhead Persistent Infrared (Next-Gen OPIR) Geosynchronous Earth Orbit
(GEO) missile warning satellites with a proven bus, new hardened sensors, and auxiliary payloads for increased resilience.
The space segment for GEO missile warning satellites consists of a resilient architecture providing real time persistent global
equatorial infrared coverage. The first GEO satellite is required in 2026.

FY 2025 Plans:
Continue Phase 2 efforts to build and deliver 2 GEO Space Vehicles (SVs). Execute activities to support SV#1 delivery including
final space/ground/launch integration, SV testing, and ground test activities. Implement corrective actions for defects and issues
discovered during environmental testing. Continue build, integration, and test of SV#2 including system-level assembly and testing

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2024      FY 2025      FY 2026
to enable discovery and correction of defects critical to launch. Finish Mission Payload (MPL)#2 build, assembly, integration,
and conduct environmental Thermal Vacuum (TVAC) testing. Continue Enterprise planning and support for launch activities and
secure communications including government-furnished cryptologic units, long-haul communications, etc. Rapidly respond to
updated intelligence on threats and implement system resiliency and situational awareness necessary to operate in the contested
space domain. Activities may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation,
prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial and international opportunities.
FY 2026 Plans:
FY 2026 funds are required to execute on-orbit testing and interim contractor operations support for SV#1, preserve 2027 initial
launch capability (ILC) for SV#2, perform space/ground integration activities, and continue build and integration activities for
SV#2. Continue executing ground system mission data processing, command and control, and integration development to support
SV#1 and SV#2. Conduct system level assembly and test for SV#2, including space-to-ground testing to enable discovery
and correction of defects critical to launch. Conduct SV#2 space vehicle baseline test, electromagnetic interference test and
acoustic test. Conduct environmental thermal-vacuum testing for the fully assembled SV#2. Rapidly respond to implement system
resiliency and situational awareness necessary to operate in the contested space domain. Activities may include, but are not
limited to program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation, risk reduction, prototyping, and activities that
may leverage commercial, U.S. Government partnership, and international opportunities to respond to existing and emerging
adversarial threats with speed and agility.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2026 decreased $26.654M due to completion of most of the non-recurring engineering and long-lead procurements for the
program, delivery of the second mission payload, and completion of a significant portion of the build and integration work for
SV#2. This phase of the program entails primarily on-orbit support to SV#1 and integration testing for SV#2 in preparation for a
2027 launch.
