$$, $$31d2363a5d20be1ba2b3e44cca55f9ed3cd21bb970bf6a9d9dd60f750f21a771$$, $${"A": "5fa489b32b859c4d9723b9232f5d8ef05ec1efe9cfec8fe35ed9e201c8f6f01e", "D": "d4fdf923ba776b98bda680220afe7660b2fb7f78e25f4cb026ad0b29031d9620", "E": "f85af38339e98dffee08d249ea7b02218224ffe19c7bb7ce3104f1848baa4750"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY26/USAF/FY26 Space Force Research and Development Test and Evaluation.pdf$$, 479, $$2026-05-07T23:57:02.622579+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0604343F$$, 2027, $$Advanced Tanker Systems (ATS) is a continuation of the efforts previously started in PE 0605057F, Next Generation Air-refueling System (NGAS).

Developing future tanker capability and recapitalizing the Air Force's aging tanker fleet is a top priority for the Department of the Air Force, in direct support of the
National Defense Strategy's vision of ‘Peace Through Strength.' The pacing challenge and the operational realities of the Indo-Pacific theater demand a paradigm
shift in aerial refueling. The current tanker fleet, designed for uncontested airspace, presents a critical vulnerability. Its reliance on large, centralized basing and its
significant electronic and physical signature make it a high-value target, jeopardizing the Joint Force's ability to project power and sustain high-tempo operations over
vast distances. ATS directly addresses this capability gap, evolving aerial refueling from a simple logistics function into a resilient, combat-enabling capability. The FY
2024 NGAS Analysis of Alternatives (AoA) provided conclusions that tankers will need to be more survivable to operate in a contested environment.

ATS is a modernization program designed to improve the connectivity, survivability, and overall viability of the Department of War's current and future tanker fleets.
The program directly addresses the challenges of operating in highly-contested, near-peer environments by ensuring the tanker fleet can effectively support the Joint
Force's global reach, power projection, and persistence. ATS will focus on developing and integrating platform-agnostic systems that comply with military open-source
architecture standards, ensuring rapid adaptability and interoperability across platforms.

Program activities will be executed using a modern, digital acquisition framework. This includes the extensive use of digital engineering and modeling, rapid prototyping,
and iterative requirements refinement based on continuous market research and post-AoA studies. This agile approach is designed to mature and de-risk critical
technologies before they are integrated, accelerating development timelines while reducing lifecycle costs.

ATS program funding provides for technology transfer, maturation, and prototyping across four main lines of effort, all of which are critical to the long-term viability of the
tanker enterprise. These efforts include 1) Connectivity will ensure the tanker serves as a critical node in the Joint All-Domain Command & Control (JADC2) architecture
by implementing secure, multi-level communication suites, 2) Survivability will mature advanced defensive systems and threat detection capabilities to increase the
ability to operate and persist in contested airspace, 3) Autonomy will be explored to reduce crew workload and enhance mission efficiency through capabilities like

 autonomous refueling. Funding provides for operational concept exploration, technology studies, industry integration assessments and strategic planning, and system
 architecture development, and 4) Advanced Air Refueling Systems will mature novel concepts for air refueling and explore next-generation boom designs to improve
 reliability and compatibility with a wide range of receiver aircraft. The technologies developed are intended for spiral integration onto the KC-135, KC-46, as well as future
 tanker platforms through requirements maturation.

Program management support costs include, but are not limited to, systems engineering, contractor support services, and civilian pay. Program support cost efforts
consist of, but are not limited to, contract services and government costs.

This requirement supports performance of a full financial audit as required by title 10 U.S.C. Chapter 9A, Sec 240-D.

This program element included all necessary expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver weapon system capability. The use of such program funds would be in
addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 0605829F, 0605831F, 0605833F, and 0605898F.

This effort is in Budget Activity 4, Advanced Component Development and Prototypes (ACD&P), because efforts are necessary to evaluate integrated technologies,
representative modes or prototype systems in a high fidelity and realistic operating environment.$$, $$Advanced Tanker Systems (ATS) is a continuation of the efforts previously started in PE 0605057F, Next Generation Air-refueling System (NGAS).

