C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2024     FY 2025      FY 2026
Title: SCN Enhancements and Deficiency Resolution                                                                                         8.797       0.000        0.000
Description: Provides system enhancements, deficiency resolution, test, cyber security, requirements management, and system
architecture support to the Satellite Control Network (SCN) utilizing enterprise developed technologies or capabilities, when
applicable. Additionally, the SCN is investigating multiple cyber defense tools for integration onto the SCN baseline.

FY 2025 Plans:
N/A.
FY 2026 Plans:
N/A.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
N/A.
Title: Satellite Operations Transmit and Receive                                                                                        18.591      23.937         20.801
Description: Provides enterprise transmit, receive and resource management solutions to enable continuous satellite operations
(SATOPS) from benign to contested, degraded and operationally-denied environments as part of Data Transport Receive Network
(DTRN) efforts. Provides updates to SCN legacy system capability shortfalls. These updates include modernization of current
scheduling, resource management, and development execution for future integrated and automated resource management and
scheduling services. Additionally, the SCN will integrate with multiple enterprise cyber defense tools as part of the baseline.

FY 2025 Plans:
Continue the phased modernization of capabilities supporting satellite operations transmit and receive for both the current
and evolving future demand. Adapt as necessary to address user priorities to responsively support mission needs. Continue
foundational Enterprise Resource Manager (ERM) system development efforts, iteratively maturing the design to assure ground
resource integration, management, and automation. Continue to deliver enhancements and deficiency resolution for Satellite
Operations Transmit and Receive efforts. Rapidly respond to implement system resiliency and situational awareness necessary
to operate in the contested space domain. Activities may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical

Operational Systems Development

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2024    FY 2025      FY 2026
analysis, experimentation, risk reduction, prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial, U.S. Government partnership,
and international opportunities to respond to existing and emerging adversarial threats with speed and agility.
FY 2026 Plans:
Continue the phased modernization of capabilities supporting satellite operations transmit and receive for both the current
and evolving future demand. Adapt as necessary to address user priorities to responsively support mission needs. Support
development of phased array, mobile, or other antenna/site improvements. Continue development of ERM interfaces for
commercial apertures access and machine-to-machine data transfers, Deliver an ERM interface control document (ICD) for
Satellite Operations Centers (SOCs), an automated scheduler with Radio Frequency Interference (RFI) deconfliction, and
complete development of the interface which is a key function for supporting scheduling of Satellite Communication Augmentation
Resource (SCAR) phased array antennas. Continue to deliver enhancements and deficiency resolution for Satellite Operations
Transmit and Receive efforts.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2026 decreased due to ramp-down of ERM Minimum Viable Capability Release (MVCR) development.
Title: Satellite C2 Augmentation Services                                                                                             14.597     21.479         15.006
Description: Provides both Federal and commercial satellite command and control (C2) services to augment SCN capabilities.
Augmented services are planned to be deployed in a phased approach to address early integration and security concerns while
providing increased C2 diversity and capacity to reduce the risk of congestion on the SCN.

FY 2025 Plans:
Continue development and modernization of augmentation services, including integration of services into Enterprise Resource
Manager (ERM), and implementation of system resiliency and situational awareness necessary to operate in the contested
space domain. Support the final year of initial operations of the Federal Augmentation capability. Continue pursuit of commercial
augmentation solutions. On-board missions to utilize augmentation as prescribed by user-driven need. Continue to deliver
enhancements and deficiency resolution for Satellite C2 Augmentation Services efforts.
FY 2026 Plans:
Continue development of augmentation services, including integration of these services into ERM. Continue pursuit of
operationalized commercial antenna access solutions, to include cyber-secure antenna network brokering via prototype Joint
Antenna Marketplace (JAM) development. Demonstrate operational feasibility for contact operations for at least two Satellite
Operations Centers (SOCs) and at least two commercial antenna provider networks. Continue to deliver enhancements and
deficiency resolution for Satellite C2 Augmentation Services efforts.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:

Operational Systems Development

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2024    FY 2025      FY 2026
FY 2026 decreased due to conclusion of initial operations support for Federal Augmentation.
Title: Cyber-secure Mission Data Transport                                                                                             27.420     27.715         50.234
Description: Provides a scalable, resilient, cyber-secure network communications architecture and infrastructure delivering
intelligent, enterprise data and information transport for execution of warfighting functions. Supports worldwide ground
communications transport for USSF, other DoD Services, Intelligence Community, and Joint All-Domain Command and Control
by fielding an industry standards-based mission data network featuring interoperability, cyber security (to include Zero Trust
networking), cloud connectivity and multidomain facilitation. Addresses identified "Kill Chain” gaps, legacy system obsolescence,
bandwidth constraints, stovepipes and cost inefficiency.

FY 2025 Plans:
Execute the initial full year of development, integration, and fielding, following FY 2024 contract award. Continue development
of the meshONE-Terrestrial (meshONE-T) system to deliver a modern, scalable, resilient, cyber-secure network communications
architecture for mission data transport. Continue deployment of new capabilities and upgrades, new network nodes, and
communication to support warfighter-prioritized mission partners and locations. Continue to deliver enhancements and deficiency
resolution for Cyber-secure Mission Data Transport efforts, and improve timely, secure movement of data between USSF
systems and downstream warfighting service elements, improve resiliency and extensibility, efficiently connect data producers
and consumers, and close capability gaps. Perform pre-operations support for existing meshONE-T network mission partners
and users. Activities may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation,
prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial and international opportunities.
FY 2026 Plans:
Continue expansion and development of the meshONE-Terrestrial (meshONE-T) system to deliver a modern, scalable, resilient,
cyber-secure network communications architecture for mission data transport. Continue deployment of new capabilities and
upgrades to include but not limited to satellite communications (SATCOM), additional Zero Trust architecture enhancements,
and delivery of initial Rapid Deployable capabilities. Deploy additional network nodes and communication to support warfighter-
prioritized mission partners and locations, completing a significant portion of the global mesh buildout. Continue to deliver
enhancements and deficiency resolution. Perform pre-operations support for the growing meshONE-T network mission partners
and users. Rapidly respond to implement system resiliency and situational awareness necessary to operate in the contested
space domain. Activities may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation,
risk reduction, prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial, U.S. Government partnership, and international
opportunities to respond to existing and emerging adversarial threats with speed and agility.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:

Operational Systems Development

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2024     FY 2025      FY 2026
FY 2026 increased due to escalation of effort to meet node deployment requirements, onboard additional mission partners, and to
support pre-operations for the expanding mesh network.
Title: Enterprise Systems Engineering and Integration (SE&I)                                                                             7.674      8.441          7.739
Description: SE&I manages the government-controlled system and subsystem level baseline requirements including analysis
of future changes to the fielded baseline. SE&I provides "government as the integrator" engineering support to ensure multiple
separate modernizations and the sustainment baselines are synchronized. SE&I will develop and recommend investment
strategies to keep the Satellite Control Network (SCN) and Cyber-secure Mission Data Transport operating into the future.

FY 2025 Plans:
Continue Program Office support and SE&I efforts as required for integration, development and modernization across data
transmit, receive and transport capabilities. Provide systems and subsystem level definition, baseline, architecture, integration
planning, test, and support for the SCN and augmentation services. Additionally, SE&I will provide support to Space Systems
Command (SSC) initiatives supporting Data Transport Receive Network (DTRN) activities. Continue to support enhancements and
deficiency resolution in fielded SCN systems, to include newly-delivered capabilities, and implementation of system resiliency and
situational awareness necessary to operate in the contested space domain.
FY 2026 Plans:
Continue Program Office support and SE&I efforts as required for integration, development and modernization across data
transmit, receive and transport capabilities. Provide systems and subsystem level definition, baseline, architecture, integration
planning, test, and support for the Satellite Control Network (SCN) and augmentation services. Additionally, SE&I will provide
support to Space Systems Command (SSC) initiatives supporting Data Transport Receive Network (DTRN) activities. Continue
to support enhancements and deficiency resolution in fielded SCN systems, to include newly-delivered capabilities, and
implementation of system resiliency and situational awareness necessary to operate in the contested space domain.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2026 decreased due to operational acceptance of FAS and AST.
