capability. Potential investigation activities will include detailed mission and cost analyses, investigation of the harsh rocket plume
interactions with landing surfaces, evaluation of rocket landing capabilities at austere sites, and human factors at landing sites.
Investments will also determine the ability to airdrop cargo after reentry, will assess in-flight communications to the rocket, will
test cargo environments and novel cargo "loadmaster” designs for rapid load/unload, and will evaluate rocket detectability and
vulnerability.

FY 2025 Plans:
In the FY 2024 and FY 2025, the Rocket Cargo effort and funding were reported in PE 1206616SF/Space Advanced Technology
Development/Demo, Project 633834/Integrated Space Technology Demonstrations. FY 2024 funding was $42.200 million and FY
2025 funding is $54.200 million.
FY 2026 Plans:
Continue:
- And complete tasks for flight readiness and delivery site CONOPS for a demonstration launch of technologies to transport 30 to
100 tons of cargo to an austere site.
- Airdrop S&T on the payload mid-air system deployment capabilities from an airdropped container or capsule system.
- Quantitative S&T assessment of the rocket detectability and vulnerability, anchored with rocket flight data, to determine
implications for military missions; incorporate these details into detailed mission analysis and the capability return on investment.

Complete:
- Multi-disciplinary S&T to expand commercial rocket capabilities for DOD global cargo delivery on tactical timelines.
- Investigations of rocket landing viability over a broader range of unprepared sites and non-standard landing surfaces relevant to
rocket delivery directly to the point of need, including landing pad material surface degradation and human factors at the landing
site.
