Description: This effort is not a new start. In FY 2026, the Payload Delivery Systems effort and funding transferred within this
Program Element from Project 633834, Integrated Space Technology Demonstrations, sub effort under the Transformational
Technology Development effort to Project 630321, Space Warfighter Technologist Capabilities, to provide increased transparency
and traceability of USSF S&T Vanguard and WARTECH efforts and activities.

The Vanguard Prospect Payload Delivery System is a Spacedrop Demonstration which expands upon the Rocket Cargo
Vanguard, which leveraged the multi-billion-dollar commercial investments in large reusable launch vehicles to extend the
commercial rocket capabilities and create a novel DOD solution for global reach. While Rocket Cargo S&T explored downmass
and cargo delivery via rocket re-entry, this effort will investigate cargo downmass and delivery via capsule spacedrop and re-entry.
The re-entry capsule approach has potential for increased cargo mass per launch and a broad diversity of launch solutions from
medium-lift to super-heavy lift launch vehicles. The capsule S&T is inherently multi-disciplinary and multi-domain across air and
space.

Note: This effort is dual funded (USAF and USSF) starting in FY 2026. The scope shown here includes all the scope (both USAF
and USSF) as both funding lines contribute to that scope. The funding shown here is only the USSF funding. The USAF funding
can be found in USAF PE 0603032F, Future AF Integrated Technology Demos.

FY 2025 Plans:
In FY 2025, the Payload Delivery System effort and funding were reported as an sub-effort under the Transformational
Technology Development effort in PE 1206616SF/Space Advanced Technology Development/Demo, Project 633834/Integrated
Space Technology Demonstrations. FY 2025 funding was $18.824 million.
FY 2026 Plans:
Complete:
- Design and development of a multi-ton prototype capsule for demonstration of spacedrop, re-entry, and cargo
deployment concepts for air/land/sea.
- Modeling and simulation of the capsule re-entry aerodynamics, stability, heating, and technologies for rapid hypersonic
deceleration.

Expand:
- Studies of capsule payload environments and survivability, from spacedrop to payload delivery.
- Analyses of re-entry communications and plasma black-out.
