C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
Made progress with the Software Defined Radio, Common Flight Safety System and other projects directed to these efforts.
Continued to conduct experiments and demonstrations of kinetic and directed energy weapon concepts to prove feasibility and
facilitate transition in air to air, long range strike, and maritime strike mission areas. Evaluated industrial base implementation
of agile acquisition initiatives like open systems architecture and digital engineering for future capabilities. Explored low-cost
initiatives such as ground-launched and air-to-air.
FY 2027 Plans:
Continue Software Defined Radio NSA Certification Efforts and radio development, Common Flight Safety System development
and environmental testing. Continue Long Range Kill Chain Modeling, Simulation, and Analysis tool development. Continue
prototyping and demonstrations of adaptable affordable mass weapon systems, subsystems, and components to prove feasibility
and manufacturability. Plan and prepare for prototype transition activities into air-to-air, long-range strike, and maritime strike
mission areas as appropriate. Continue to incentivize industry base implementation of agile, adaptable acquisition tenants such as
modular open systems architecture, digital engineering, and advanced manufacturing for future weapon capabilities.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Funding decreased due to the Software Defined Radio element transition from Disruptive Future Division to Long Range Strike.
Title: Warfighter Analytics                                                                                                              1.805      12.238          9.678
Description: Enables the conduct of rapid acquisition/prototyping efforts and MS&A validation through integration of empirical
data derived from MS&A, prototypes and demonstrations, shaped by stakeholder engagements. Enables Air Force enterprise
weapons capability planning through the generation and execution of new and emerging requirements and trade space analysis,
the outcome of which feeds the semi-annual, joint General Officer Steering Group, the Weapons Conclave (WEPCON), a
joint decision-making body co-chaired by the USAF Program Acquisition Executive (PAE) for Weapons and the USN Program
Executive Officer for Unmanned Aviation and Strike Weapons (PEO U&W).

FY 2026 Plans:
Conducted multiple analytical assessments in accordance with the Defense Planning Scenario with key stakeholders. Assessed
Analysis of Alternatives results to prototype weapon system and subsystem concepts. Analyzed feasibility of attributes and
technologies for incorporation into requisite phases of the acquisition life cycle in concert with key stakeholders. Transitioned
armament concepts with effects to program offices, war games and flag exercises. Established new M&S capabilities to expand
modeling to predict and better validate products.
FY 2027 Plans:
Expand on foundational M&S program development and operational analysis tactics, techniques and procedures. Synchronize
research efforts with developmental weapon programs and portfolio capability gap road maps. Broaden analysis iterations


