        Change Summary Explanation
        FY 2025 budget request increased by $9.117 million due to $14.999 million increase for Air Force internal reprogramming for GPS receiver development and
        $5.882 million decrease for Small Business Innovation Research/Small Business Technology Transfer (SBIR/STTR).

        FY 2026 budget request decreased by $1.464 million due to Small Business Innovation Research/Small Business Technology Transfer (SBIR/STTR).

        The FY 2026 President's Budget submittal did not reflect the FY 2027 through FY 2030 funding. Therefore, an explanation of the changes between the two
        budget positions for FY 2027 cannot be made in a relevant manner.

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
Title: Embedded GPS/INS - Modernized (EGI-M)                                                                                           75.227      31.700        68.300
Description: Embedded Global Positioning System/Inertial Navigation System - Modernized (EGI-M) is a combined GPS/INS
aircraft position, navigation, and timing system. The program upgrades the legacy EGI design to enhance resiliency against
existing and emerging adversarial navigational warfare threats. Design features, such as interface standardization and software
modularity to incorporate alternative navigation and timing sources, aim to reduce DoW cost and timelines to respond to newly
identified threats and enhance current force capabilities. EGI-M incorporates M-Code and Automatic Dependent Surveillance-
Broadcast (ADS-B) Out compliance capability into EGI receivers while addressing parts obsolescence, reducing configuration
count from 260+ to a desired end-state of 16, and decreasing production and sustainment costs.

FY 2026 Plans:
Complete Spiral 1 Formal Qualification Testing. Continue Spiral 2 Software Development. Begin LN-351 PRU system deliveries.
FY 2027 Plans:
Complete LN-351 Delta Hardware Qualification Testing. Complete Spiral 2 Formal Qualification Testing. Continue LN-351 PRU
system deliveries. Begin LN-300 PRU system builds.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Funding increased due to test/integration of long-term M-code solution for additional platform(s).
Title: Miniaturized Airborne GPS Receiver 2000 - Modernization (MAGR-2K-M)                                                            17.500        8.600         27.700
Description: Miniaturized Airborne GPS Receiver 2000 - Modernization (MAGR-2K-M) is an aircraft GPS receiver. The program
increases MAGR-2K legacy resiliency against existing and emerging adversarial navigational warfare threats while reducing cost
and timelines to incorporate future capabilities in response to emerging threats. MAGR-2K-M incorporates M-Code capability into
MAGR-2K legacy receivers while addressing parts obsolescence and providing a pathway to ADS-B Out implementation. Military
code (M-code) was designed to further improve the anti-jamming capabilities and secure access of the military GPS signals. Since
M-code is transmitted in frequencies already in use by previous military codes, a modernized GPS will deliver improved capability
to counter current and emerging PNT threats and enable military operations in a Navigation Warfare environment where current
legacy receiver performance would be compromised.

FY 2026 Plans:
Program finalizing test and integration of latest GPS Receiver Application Model (GRAM) Software into the MAGR-2K-M receiver
to prepare for fielding. Continue preparing for PEO certification (Milestone C).
FY 2027 Plans:

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
Develop an additional software configuration required to support the final MGUE Inc 1 design. Continue Integration/testing for
transition into production (Milestone C decision anticipated 4th Qtr FY 2026).
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Funding increased due to additional software configuration development.
Title: Resilient EGI (R-EGI)                                                                                                         107.047      46.000        168.300
Description: Resilient Embedded Global Positioning System/Inertial Navigation System (R-EGI) program establishes a
Government Reference Architecture (GRA) embodying modular open systems architecture (MOSA), enabling and accelerating
the transition and operational insertion of future resilient PNT DoD capabilities. R-EGI delivers improved PNT resiliency through
the rapid design, development, test, and transition of science and technology efforts to operational PNT systems. R-EGI enables
the design and development of various aircraft PNT Line Replaceable Units (LRUs) that are rapidly upgradeable to counter
evolving adversarial threats; the program demonstrates the GRA through prototyping of an open R-EGI LRU. The program
matures, prototypes, and tests PNT technologies/systems and enables transition paths to flow new technologies into the R-EGI
LRU and iterate as required to support the warfighter.

FY 2026 Plans:
Continue testing and integration of F-15 Medium Form Factor (MFF) PRUs to prepare for production decision and subsequent
fielding. Continue validation of software development iso a reproducible, government-owned Level 3 Technical Data Package and
execute Functional Configuration Audit/Physical Configuration Audits to enable future competitive procurement.
FY 2027 Plans:
Resume development and testing of the F-16 Large Form Factor (LFF) and testing and integration of the B-52 MFF. Begin
development and testing for AC/MC-130J, C-130J, C-17, KC-135, and SAOC platforms. Continue validation of software
development iso a reproducible, government-owned Level 3 Technical Data Package and execute Functional Configuration Audit/
Physical Configuration Audits to enable future competitive procurement.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Funding increased due to additional form factor (LFF) development and additional platforms (F-16, B-52, AC/MC-130J, C-130J,
C-17, KC-135, and SAOC).
Title: Positioning Navigation Timing Software Defined User Equipment (PNT SDUE)                                                       15.139      17.721        166.700
Description: Positioning Navigation Timing Software Defined User Equipment (PNT SDUE) will develop a Satellite Navigation
(SATNAV) Software Defined Receiver (SSDR) hosted on a Commercial Off-the-Shelf (COTS) Field Programmable Gate Array
(FPGA) delivering an M-Code receiver with agile reprogramming capability to provide robust, resilient PNT against navigational
warfare (NAVWAR) and cyber threats utilizing a government owned technical baseline. The program will also develop Software

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
Defined Antenna Electronics (SDAE) utilizing COTS FPGA equipment to support the ingest of new satellite signals/capabilities,
signal processing, and the incorporation of a Global Navigation Satellite System (GNSS) capability in a software reprogrammable
environment. The GNSS receiver and antenna electronics will interface directly with Resilient EGI (R-EGI) via modular open
standard architecture. This program will transition and field advanced User Equipment capabilities for the Navigation Technology
Satellite (NTS)-3 Air Force Vanguard effort. The USAFs preferred Resilient PNT capability consists of a trinity which includes R-
EGI, SDAE, and SSDR.

FY 2026 Plans:
Continue Digital Engineering Other Transaction Authority (OTA) and Design Agent OTA efforts. Building and evaluating physical
SDAE prototypes and developing a digital twin model for the SDAE.
FY 2027 Plans:
Continue Digital Engineering OTA and Design Agent OTA efforts. Building and evaluating physical SDAE prototypes and
developing digital twin models for both the SDAE and SSDR.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Funding increased due to additional testing and development of SDAE prototypes and digital twin models for both the SDAE and
SSDR. Additionally, the large increase in funds corresponds to SDUE's development of fieldable prototypes within the 5-year
Rapid Prototyping window. SDUE is currently in year 3 of a 5-year MTA.
Title: MGUE Inc 1 System/Platform Integration and Performance Certification                                                            0.000       0.000          1.000
Description: Integration of MGUE Inc 1 receiver form factors into lead platforms in support of developmental and operational (or
field) test events. Conduct technical and operational modernization impact analysis for MGUE lead platform integration.

FY 2026 Plans:
N/A
FY 2027 Plans:
Complete Technical Evaluation and Follow-On Operational Test & Evaluation (FOT&E) test events for GPNTS integrated with
MGUE on board an Arleigh-Burke Class Destroyer (DDG).
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Funding increased due to ramp up of testing activities.
Title: MGUE Inc 2 Miniature Serial Interface (MSI) Receiver Card Rapid Prototyping                                                     0.000       0.000        101.891
Description: The MGUE Inc 2 program will develop M-Code receiver technology for additional applications (space receivers,
precision guided munitions, and handheld receivers) to meet Service requirements. MGUE Inc 2 MSI Receiver Card Rapid

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025     FY 2026      FY 2027
prototyping builds on the Application-Specific Integrated Circuit (ASIC) post-Preliminary Design Review (PDR) progress and will
develop, integrate, produce, and test M-Code capable, low size and power GPS MSI form factor to include a Next Gen ASIC.
The MSI receiver card is to meet the needs of low size, weight and power (SWaP) ground-embedded users. However, the Next
Gen ASIC must meet the needs of the MSI form factor and be backwards compatible with Inc 1 performance requirements as a
potential functional replacement due to Inc 1 ASIC obsolescence.

Additionally, Advanced Technology/Pre-Tech includes efforts to mature technology for future GPS receivers identified in the
MGUE CDDs. These efforts aim to find innovative solutions to increase resiliency in GPS performance and improve on size,
weight, power, and cost (SWAP/C) of military receivers.

FY 2026 Plans:
N/A
FY 2027 Plans:
Contracting activities for Software Pathway (SWP) development contract option. Additional plans include but are not limited
to special studies on developing integrated Assured Positioning, Navigation and Timing System and Multi-Global Navigation
Satellite System (M-GNSS) receivers, complete security certification, formal MSI Functional Qualification Test, and Functional
Configuration Audit/Physical Configuration Audit, technical analysis, experimentation, risk reduction and prototyping activities,
MGUE Test Program PA, Cooperative RDT&E PA, added Satellite Signal Usage for Resilient Equipment (ASSURE) PA, and
development and testing of Military Underwater Navigation System-M-Code (MUNS-M).
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Funding increased due to initiation of contracting activities for Software Pathway (SWP) development contract.
Title: MGUE Inc 2 Handheld (HH)                                                                                                         0.000      0.000         17.859
Description: The MGUE Inc 2 Handheld (HH) effort will develop a joint common modernized HH receiver that will provide M-
code, anti-spoof, and anti-jam capabilities, with significant improvements in size, weight, and power. The goal of the MGUE Inc
2 HH risk reduction activities is to reduce development risk for the MGUE Inc 2 HH receiver through feedback from the rapid
prototyping process and multiple joint service demonstration events.

FY 2026 Plans:
N/A
FY 2027 Plans:

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                      FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
Conduct key Miniature Serial Interface (MSI) technology integration and test activities, prototype hardware, software, and critical
component maturation, ultimately driving toward initial production readiness. Activities may include, but are not limited to program
office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation, risk reduction, and prototyping.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Funding increased due to initial start up of key Miniature Serial Interface (MSI) technology integration and testing activities.
Title: MGUE Inc 2 Aviation/Maritime Receiver Card                                                                                           0.000       0.000         89.994
Description: The MGUE Inc 2 Aviation/Maritime effort will develop an Aviation/Maritime receiver card that will provide M-code,
anti-spoof, and anti-jam capabilities addressing Inc 1 ASIC obsolescence. The MGUE Inc 2 Aviation/Maritime effort will consist of
a risk reduction study with a follow-on Middle Tier of Acquisitions (MTA). The risk reduction study will primarily aid in establishing
requirements, defining an overarching funding profile, and evaluating the competitive marketplace in support of the MTA which will
deliver the receiver prototype. This prototype builds upon MGUE Inc 2 MSI Receiver Card Rapid Prototyping Major Thrust ASIC
efforts to address Aviation/Maritime capabilities.

FY 2026 Plans:
N/A
FY 2027 Plans:
Support risk reduction study activities exploring application of Military-Code (M-Code) receiver and RMP capability into Aviation/
Maritime applications. Contracting activities to support Release Request for Protype Proposal, and contract award to develop,
prototype, integrate and test a Maritime and Aviation Receiver Card (MAVRC) form factor for use in aviation and maritime
applications.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Funding increased due to additional support office activities for risk reduction study.
Title: PNT Resiliency, Mods, and Improvements (RMI)                                                                                         9.104      20.178         69.036
Description: Conduct studies and analysis of PNT systems and requirements, develop and evaluate alternative courses of action
to identify, plan and conduct PNT technology transition projects, conduct prototype and acquisition program planning, and provide
recommended solutions to Department of War and Air Force decision makers relative to navigation warfare threat evolution and
technology emergence. Efforts include but not limited to, developing an associated antenna electronics capability to capture
other than GPS signals like Multi-Global Navigation Satellite Systems, Navigation Technology Satellite-III and other commercial
solutions, operationalizing Regional Military Protection (RMP) capabilities, Multi-source PNT Radios (MPR), and alternative PNT
over hybrid satellite communications (HST).

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2025      FY 2026      FY 2027
FY 2026 Plans:
Continue studies and advanced analysis of PNT systems and requirements. Continuation of development and testing activities
for interface design requirements and evaluation of existing systems and risk with Alt-PNT technologies interface with DoW PNT
systems.
FY 2027 Plans:
Continuation of studies and advanced analysis of resilient PNT systems and requirements. Continuation of testing and
development to minimize risks syncing Alt-PNT technologies with DoW PNT systems.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Funding increased due to additional resilient and alternate PNT capabilities activities.
