Remarks
Per FY 2024 National Defense Authorization Act Section 1685(b), the Under Secretary of War for Acquisition and Sustainment shall treat the Positioning, Navigation,
and Timing Resiliency, Modifications, and Improvements program of the Air Force (PE 0604201F) as an acquisition category (ACAT) 1D program, and the authority to
manage such program may not be delegated.

 Per "M-Code Aviation Receiver Enterprise Acquisition Decision Memorandum", dated 25 Nov 2024 and signed by Mr. William A. LaPlante, Under Secretary of War for
 Acquisition and Sustainment, Military GPS User Equipment Increment 1 (MGUE Inc 1) program Space Force efforts and funding will end in FY 2027. In FY 2027, the
 Department of the Air Force will develop and fund MGUE Inc 2. This memorandum also established the designation of a Joint Program Office that will support the Joint
 Services, with the Air Force acting as the lead Service for the M-Code Aviation Receiver Enterprise Acquisition.

 Per "Service Transfer of MGUE Increment 2 from USSF to USAF" memorandum, dated 09 Apr 2025 and signed by Lt General Dale R. White, USAF, Military Deputy,
 Office of the Assistant Secretary of the Air Force (Acquisition, Technology, and Logistics) and Maj General Stephen G. Purdy, USSF, Acting Assistant Secretary of the
 Air Force for Space Acquisition and Integration, all Military GPS User Equipment Increment 2 (MGUE Inc 2) program efforts will transfer from Space Force to Air Force.

Development & Demonstration (SDD)$$, $$Beginning in FY 2027, GPS Receiver Development includes projects Military Global Positioning System User Equipment (MGUE) Increment 1 and Increment 2. MGUE
Inc 1 program is responsible for the development of standard modernized receiver form factors for the lead platforms. The program received direction in February 2014,
from the Under Secretary of War for Acquisition and Sustainment to execute a new acquisition strategy, accelerating the program to provide test units faster to facilitate
military end users.

 The MGUE program received a Milestone B decision in January 2017. MGUE Inc 1 has completed the APB Milestones for PEO Certification of the MGUE Inc 1 Aviation/
 Maritime card for the Maritime Domain lead platform, the Arleigh-Burke Class Destroyer (DDG). The remaining program exit criteria for the MGUE Inc 1 program is tied
 to the successful completion of operational testing for the Maritime Domain lead platform. The Maritime Domain lead platform's developmental test events, including
 Independent Verification & Validation (IV&V) testing and AEGIS Integration Event (AIE) for GPNTS combat certification are scheduled to complete in 2026.

 The JROC approved the MGUE Inc 2 CDD on 6 April 2018. The Air Force Service Acquisition Executive approved the MGUE Inc 2 Acquisition Strategy to include
 designation of two MTA Rapid Prototype efforts: 1) MSI Receiver Cards to include Next-Generation (Next Gen) Application Specific Integrated Circuit (ASIC) and 2)
 Joint, Modernized Handheld Receiver. The SAE has approved the transition to a SWP following completion of MSI MTA in 2025 to finish MSI development. Additionally,
 the MGUE Inc 2 program received direction for the study of an MGUE Inc 2 Aviation/Maritime receiver card (MAVRC) program and development of an acquisition
 strategy based on ASIC obsolescence for Inc 1.

 Acquisition strategy is modify and modernize existing legacy PNT systems to incorporate major enhancements such as Global Positioning System (GPS) M-Code, ADS-
 B Out, and alternative PNT solutions to GPS while reducing lifecycle costs through common sustainment practices and economies of scale. Design, development, and
 testing efforts, to include the development of government owned reference architectures for rapid capability insertion. Integration and operational testing of completed
 PNT solutions are accomplished by individual platforms and weapons systems. This approach uses cost plus fixed fee (CPFF) contract types based on acquisition
 phase and risk with a mix between competition and sole-source strategies. Modifications to legacy receivers are acquired via Engineering Change Proposals (ECP)/
 Task Orders on existing contracts. Other Transaction Authorities (OTA) and industry consortiums are used to support prototyping and open standards development for
 new PNT solutions.

